## Chapter 1: Introduction: Capital Wars

### Capital Wars: The New Trade Wars

- The 2007-2008 **Global Financial Crisis (GFC)** was a devastating **global liquidity shock**
- By early 1980s, warnings were already present: new factors had evolved to displace the doctrine of **earnings power** as the main driver of stock prices
- The focus shifted to a specific type of money power: **Global Liquidity**—a US$130 trillion pool of footloose capital currently two-thirds bigger than World GDP

### The 2008 Crisis as a Dollar Scramble

- The GFC occurred when dramatic escalation in monetary tensions triggered a frantic scramble for US dollars
- Europe's demands alone exceeded **US$8 trillion**
- There was no automatic international lender of last resort
- With the IMF's firepower then still only counted in billions, there was no pool of reserves anywhere in the World outside the US Federal Reserve and its system of swap lines
- This system was large enough to stabilize the crisis but only just barely

> "The money power preys upon the nation in times of peace and conspires against it in times of adversity. It is more despotic than monarchy, more insolent than autocracy, more selfish than bureaucracy." — Abraham Lincoln (attributed, purportedly from a letter to Colonel William F. Elkins, November 1864, following passage of the National Bank Act, June 1864)

### Global Liquidity Defined

- **Global Liquidity**: US$130 trillion pool of footloose capital
- Currently two-thirds bigger than World GDP (Fig. 1.1)
- A pool of **safe assets** that can be readily mobilized for investment, speculation, or flight
- Highly mobile capital that flows across borders seeking returns and safety
- Central to understanding modern financial markets and economic cycles

### The Shift from Earnings Power to Money Power

- Traditional doctrine focused on **earnings power** as main stock price driver
- By 1980s, **money power** had become the dominant force
- This represents a fundamental change in how financial markets operate
- Stock prices increasingly driven by liquidity flows rather than fundamental company performance

### Why Global Liquidity Matters

- Financial flows, not high street inflation or the "real economy," drive economic cycles
- The distinction between **asset economy** and **real economy** is critical
- **John Maynard Keynes** distinguished the economy's financial and industrial spheres similarly
- Trying to stimulate the real economy with liquidity always risks creating **asset price bubbles** instead

### The Post-GFC Policy Response

- In 1987, after near-identical situation to the post-GFC era, policymakers unleashed analogous stimulus
- Result: near-flat high street prices but soaring asset prices
- A fractured, uncertain World encouraged investors to hold excessive "safe" assets
- Particularly: government bonds and US dollar assets
- Rather than putting money to work productively

### The Problem of "Safe Assets"

- When the State fails to produce sufficient safe assets, the private sector steps in with **pseudo safe-substitutes**
- These values unfortunately move **procyclically**
- Governments' austerity policies and quantitative tightening programs might not be as sound as they appear
- The mechanism: **precautionary demand for money** (hurriedly skipped over in traditional textbooks)
- This better describes the growing systemic risks than the better-known speculative motive

### The Liquidity Trap

- Global Liquidity is **never trapped**
- It waves no flag, knows no boundaries
- Shifts all over between markets and asset classes
- Can assess chances of **rising interest rates** and lead to a **liquidity trap**
- This is distinct from traditional concerns about falling interest rates

### Two Puzzling Features in Policy Debates

**First puzzle: Quantitative Easing and bond yields**
- Widespread consensus undermined by repeated Central Bank rate cuts
- When Central Bank quantitative easing (QE) lowers and does not raise term premia, bond yields fall
- Academic argument summarized by **Gagnon (2016)**: quantifies this as 67 basis points (bp) per 10% of GDP injected via QE
- Data refutes this: QE periods in the US have been **unequivocally associated with higher yields**
- Term premia rising on average 134 bp through each phase

**Second puzzle: Yield curve as recession predictor**
- Many believe the **slope of the yield curve** is an unambiguous predictor of the business cycle
- Hence, an **inverted yield curve** should warn that recession is fast approaching
- In fact, neither statement is true
- The efficiency of the Treasury yield curve as a predictor of the business cycle is analyzed elsewhere (**Howell 2018**)
- Confirms that the standard 10-2 year yield curve slope is, at best, a flaky predictor
- Different maturity spreads work at different times
- What also matters is the **curvature** of the term structure
- Slope and curvature must be assessed together
- A key component explaining curvature is the pattern of term premia
- **Term premia are liquidity phenomena**, largely reflecting excess demand for safe assets

### The 1989 Turning Point

- The liquidity shocks that **ricocheted across the World in 1989** as the Berlin Wall fell ultimately forced interest rates down
- Helped to reverse the polarity of the global financial system
- Capital faced Eastwards along what they call the **Financial Silk Road**
- Politics and people tempted too many countries, notably **China**, to lean too heavily on the US dollar and the US Treasury market for safety

### Refinancing Mechanisms vs. New Financing Mechanisms

- Today, financial markets increasingly serve as **refinancing mechanisms** rather than **new financing mechanisms**
- This makes the **capacity of capital** (balance sheet size) more important than the **cost of capital** (level of interest rates)
- The heightened supply of poor quality "safe" assets = **shadow monetary base**
- Comprises the ability of private balance sheets to roll over the huge volumes of outstanding debts left over from the GFC era

### The Ironies of Reduced Liquidity Supply

- Reduced supply of liquidity and safe assets increases the demand to hoard them
- Together these features amplify the swings in Global Liquidity
- Explain why, as the World has got bigger, it has also become more volatile
- The underlying scarcity of high-quality assets leads to **Capital Wars**
- The battleground embraces money, technology, and geopolitics
- The struggle fought out between the two key superpowers: **Chinese industry** and **American finance**

### China vs. America in Global Liquidity

- In year 2000: China accounted for 5.9% of Global Liquidity (less than one-fifth of America's share)
- China's share reached 10.1% at the time of the 2007-2008 GFC
- Today (mid-2019): China has swelled to a whopping **27.5%**, significantly out-pacing America's slipping **22.5%** slice
- **China matters hugely to both the World economy and World finance**

### Strategic Implications

- America needs to reinvigorate her industry
- China has the more pressing need to rapidly develop her financial sector
- Like history, these are **processes, not events**
- But we can still ask: will the final victor in the markets be the US dollar or a digitally based Chinese Yuan?

### Book Structure and Approach

- A **hybrid of economic and finance theory and real-World experience**
- Unlike traditional finance (which focuses on individual securities), concentrates on:
  - **Asset allocation**
  - Evaluates potential for **macro-valuation shifts** based on interaction of investment crowds and monetary institutions
- The approach is Howell's own, but influenced by:
  - **Ron Smith**
  - **Richard Portes**
  - **Helene Rey**
  - **Pavol Povala**
- In business, worked with innovative researchers:
  - **Henry Kaufman**
  - **Marty Leibowitz**
  - **Chris Mitchinson**
  - Notably **Ewen Cameron-Watt** and **Michael Baring** (late)

### Data and Implementation

- Collection and implementation of liquidity and capital flow data is the specialization of **CrossBorder Capital** (investment advisory firm set up in 1996)
- My leagues need special praise, particularly **Angela Cozzini**
- Debt to **Tula Weis** and **Lucy Kidwell** (editors at Palgrave Macmillan)
- Heartfelt thanks to long-suffering family for putting up with so much

**Publication Details:**
- London and Oxford
- November 2019
- Author: **Michael J. Howell**
- Affiliation: **CrossBorder Capital Ltd., London, UK**
- Published by **Palgrave Macmillan**
- Dedication: "To the Salomon Brothers' Diaspora"

