## Appendix: Inflation, Deflation and Valuations

### P/E Multiples and Inflation Relationship

- **Theoretical relationship**: P/E multiple and (inverted) government bond yield both drawn against annual rate of inflation
- Equity valuations include additional risk premium based on odds of default and inventory valuation losses during deflationary periods
- Although these factors likely reverse during periods of inflation, drag of higher bond yields on equity valuation levels causes relationship between equity P/E multiples and inflation to take-on humped pattern
- Bond valuations (by implication, contra-wise, valuation of real assets) display smooth downward sloping valuation curve
- **Humped relationship implies two features**: (1) equities enjoy highest real valuation levels when price inflation low (around -2%), and (2) correlation between movements in equities and bonds crucially depends upon underlying inflation regime
- At inflation threshold defining equity valuation peak, bonds and equities negatively correlated
- At higher inflation rates, valuations of bonds and stocks positively correlated
- Possible that valuation-based correlation could break-down at level of asset prices when equity earnings sufficiently strongly positively affected by rising inflation

### Japanese Market Example: Changing Correlation Structure

- Late-1980s: Correlation coefficient between Japanese stocks and bonds averaged around 0.6 (Japanese consumer price inflation stood close to 2½%)
- Late-1990s: Japanese annual inflation turned negative (around minus ½%), causing correlation between stocks/bonds to collapse to minus 0.4
- More recently with inflation on wake of 2007-2008 GFC tumbling lower to average around minus 1% annually: Japanese stock/bond correlation tumbled to minus 0.6
- **Bonds provide good hedge to equities during periods of low inflation and price deflation**

### US Historical Data: CAPE and Inflation

- **Fig. A.2**: US CAPE (cyclically-adjusted P/E) and inflation (rolling 5-year averages), 1881-2019 using Shiller database
- Plots five-year average of US CAPE against five-year average rate of consumer price inflation
- Fitted cubic relationship shows peak CAPE at close to zero inflation
- Data also support proposition that equity valuations highest at low positive inflation rates
- **Message**: Inflation matters hugely to asset allocation decisions

### Asset Valuation Conditional on Inflation

- Asset valuation conditional on inflation—not absolute criterion
- High street inflation common factor linking valuation of asset markets
- May explain why investors often compare relative valuations of equities and bonds
- Asset valuation seriously affected by inflations and deflations because both disturb future liabilities
- Common factor facilitates arbitrage between equity and bond markets
- Could explain why alternative relative valuation tools (using earnings or dividend discount model) often proved better investment tool than separately comparing bonds by yields and equities by P/E multiples
